Writing Military Aviation Thrillers and Rise of the Indie Writer Speaker: James Blatch James Blatch is a former BBC Defence Reporter and a former BBFC Film Examiner. He reported for the BBC on the UK military from, among other places, HMS Invincible (Operation Desert Fox build up), Kuwait (Ali Al Salem allied air base), the Arctic Circle as well as covering the UK air offensive during the Kosovo Conict in 1999.
Theatre Trips 2 Operation Mincemeat, Milton Keynes Wednesday 10 th June 2026 There are still seats available for this show, which started out as a fringe musical about an outlandish war plan and became a West End and Broadway smash. While Operation Mincemeat is undoubtedly brilliant, hilarious, moving and astonishing, sometimes all in the space of one dance routine, the story it s based on doesnt exactly scream: Hit stage musical!. The actual Operation Mincemeat was a crack piece of second world war deception. MI5 took the body of homeless Welsh labourer Glyndwr Michael, who had died after eating rat poison, gave him a new name (Major William Martin), armed him with fake plans about an allied invasion of Sardinia and Greece (Sicily was the real target), and deposited his uniformed body on a beach in Huelva, Spain, hoping it would reach German spies. Split Lip, the four men who turned this story into comedy, realised this didnt just have to be a story about war. It could be a topical satire on Britains public school elites as well. There was also room to explore grief, longing and feminism. Outings 3 Gressenhall Farm and Workhouse (With a coffee stop at Dereham on the way) Thursday 16th April 2026 Arrive Dereham mid-morning in time for coffee (not included). We leave Dereham at 12:00 for a very short journey to Gressenhall Farm and Workhouse. (Entry included in cost). Gressenhall Farm and Workhouse is based in a former workhouse, originally opened in 1777 as a 'House of Industry'. Now the site houses an extensive museum exploring what life was like for those who once lived and worked here. The museum allows you to stand in an evocative workhouse setting, face to face with projections of staff and inmates, and listen to the rst-hand stories. Gressenhall's farm was used to produce food for the inmates at the workhouse. Today, the farm showcases a range of rare breed animals, traditional farming techniques and reveals how farming has changed over time. Caf and gift shop on site Cost 32 (including drivers gratuity) Outings still with spaces The Cambridge Museum Thursday 19th February A small museum, with a big story and a collection of over 40,000 everyday objects. 4 Events We held our rst evening quiz night on Wednesday 26th November at the Golden Lion and we were delighted that the room was booked to capacity. Nine teams competed and were made up from existing u3a groups as well as individuals who joined up to make a team. On the night, there were lots of furrowed brows and as answers were revealed groans, sighs and 'oh yes, of course' were heard throughout the room. It was a fun evening and a massive thanks to our Ms Quiz Barbara Francis and all attendees. Many congratulations to the winners of the quiz - Perfect Strangers. 5 Christmas Past We made our own Entertainment! On the afternoon of Thursday 4th December, St Ives Corn Exchange was full of u3a members having a really fun time. Songs from the Uke-Troupe were followed by a fteen minute panto Snow White and The Magnicent Seven! The audience then got fully immersed with an energetic rendition of The Twelve Days of Christmas. They were warmed up nicely for the communal singing of seasonal songs. Finally, everyone enjoyed a glass of bucks zz and a delicious mince pie. A very jolly, holly afternoon! You can experience something of the afternoon with these videos on YouTube.: https://u3aivo.uk/we-made-our-own-entertainmen The Petanque Group Our Christmas lunch took place on Dec 9th at the St Ives Golf Club. The room was beautifully decorated for the festive season. 65 members, partners and former members sat down to a two or three course lunch followed by mince pies and coffee or tea. There was a missing vowels table quiz on Christmas carols and songs, a prize draw and a rap written for the occasion. Everyone seemed to enjoy the time spent together. Ron Meadows Art Appreciation Group Fourteen of us enjoyed a delicious lunch at the River Terrace. We were able to have one of their rooms upstairs to ourselves which made it very cosy and festive. Italian for Beginners Our group of 12 - 14 members is plodding along. Self-directed learning has meant a great deal of self-discipline to practice in between the sessions. We move along at the groups speed and have regular recaps, exercises and quizzes. The text (BBC Talk Italian 1) is backed up with audio-visual aids, other on-line Italian language programmes and handouts. It is proving an enjoyable learning experience. https://stivescambs.u3asite.uk/ u3a_groups/italian-beginners/ We need more Groups!
